{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f4e91692-e238-4026-985c-c0159518f789","content":"The repository is empty, so there's no project-specific documentation to reference. Here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS defaults to `/cores/`):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash.** The OS will write a core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, macOS SIP may block core dumps. Check with:\n   ```bash\n   csrutil status\n   ```\n   You may need to boot into Recovery Mode to allow core dumps.\n\n5. **Alternatively, use `lldb`** to catch the crash live:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp\n   (lldb) run\n   # after crash:\n   (lldb) bt           # backtrace\n   (lldb) process save-core dump.core\n   ```\n\n6. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb ./MyApp -c /cores/core.12345\n   (lldb) bt all\n   ```\n\n**Key note for NativeAOT:** Since there's no managed runtime, `lldb` works directly with native symbols. Publish with `-p:StripSymbols=false` to preserve symbols for meaningful stack traces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"653a1399-dc48-4c6c-b7c7-3fe1f4e9e1ae","outputTokens":346,"requestId":"4192:34F1C:664663B:6F7C748:69F163D3"},"id":"f483c68a-f598-4f9e-b3e7-82d5fe49876d","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:50:23.562Z","parentId":"0d93f07f-28e7-4829-999b-403511812ea2"}
